Continuous and non-destructive X-ray fluorescence (XRF) element scanning was carried out at 1 mm resolution on the split sediment cores, corresponding to an overall sampling resolution of ~10 years and 1-year resolution in the period overlapping with instrumental records. The sediment core surfaces were covered with a 4 μm-thick thin film to avoid contamination of the scanning instruments. All XRF scanning measurements were conducted with a generator setting of 10 KV and a sampling time of 20 s. The irradiated dimensions of the core surface are 15 × 1 mm2. The split sediment cores were freeze-dried before scanning to avoid the influence of water content on the results of XRF116. The geochemical elements were calibrated using the immobile element titanium (Ti) to isolate the proportion of changes associated with climate:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
